<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h1>Tutorial 44. Manual Calculation of Adjustments to the Pattern of a Corset Cut One Piece with Shoulder Straps.</h1>
<p><strong>Let us take a certain example of a corset cut one piece with shoulder straps. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I draw a table as usual and fill in the initial pattern measurements and my client’s measurements. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>First of all, let us analyze the values in the table </strong>by comparing client’s measurements with pattern measurements to see whether the initial pattern needs to be adjusted down or up and what things need to be taken into account in further calculations.</p>
<p><strong>Let us find the difference between Bust Princess Seam Width on the client and on the pattern to see whether we need to shift the fold line of the centre front piece. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Bust Princess Seam Width shows you where the bust princess seams are placed on the garment. </strong></p>
<p>It is 21cm on the client and 18cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>21cm – 18cm = 3cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>This means either half of the folded centre front piece needs to be made 1.5cm wider. </strong></p>
<p>When I put the pattern to the fabric fold line, I will shift it 1.5cm so as to make the piece bigger.</p>
<p><strong>I write 1.5cm in line 7 of column 3. </strong></p>
<p>But if I put it to the fabric fold line with a shift, the centre front piece will become 1.5cm along the full length. To keep this in mind, I put 1.5cm in all lines of the Bust Princess Seam Width column which refer to circumference lines affected by this adjustment.</p>
<p><strong>So we have shifted the fold line of the centre front piece 1.5cm outwards. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Next, I need to put the front side seam line in place. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The front side seam line is determined by two measurements: Bust Width Front and Under-Bust Width Front. </strong>Its position is calculated as the difference between client’s measurement and pattern measurement.</p>
<p>And, of course, we must account for that 3cm added to the centre front piece.</p>
<p><strong>Do not forget that our measurements don’t include any seam allowances. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Bust Width Front: </strong>it is 60cm on the client and 46cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>We have already added 1.5cm from either end of the bust line on the centre front piece, i.e. a total of 3cm. </strong></p>
<p><strong>46cm + 3cm = 49cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>Then:</strong></p>
<p><strong>60cm – 49cm = 11cm</strong></p>
<p>I divide it in half between the two sides of the front. As the result, I need to shift either front side seam line 5.5cm outwards at the bust line level to put this seam in place on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>I write 5.5cm in line 1 of column 4. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Adjustments at the under-bust line level are calculated the same way.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Under-Bust Width Front: </strong>it is 45cm on the client and 38cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>We have already added 1.5cm from either end of the under-bust line on the centre front piece, i.e. a total of 3cm. </strong></p>
<p><strong>38cm + 3cm = 41cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>Then:</strong></p>
<p><strong>45cm – 41cm = 4cm</strong></p>
<p>I divide it in half between the two sides of the front. As the result, I need to shift either front side seam line 2cm outwards at the under-bust line level to put the seam in place on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>I write 2cm in line 2 of column 4. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The new front side seam line has a very noticeable incline </strong>because of a significant difference in the calculated adjustment values: 5.5cm at the bust line level vs. 2cm at the under-bust line level.</p>
<p><strong>As I said before, I highly recommend you never change the initial configuration or curve of the side seam line, apart from very rare cases.</strong> It is simply easier to use this pattern this way.</p>
<p><strong>Instead, we will adopt a fixed value by which we will shift the entire front side seam line outwards. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Let us see what is happening with Bust Circumference, Under-Bust Circumference, Waist Circumference, and Stomach Circumference to determine this fixed side seam adjustment value. </strong>Even a quick look at the difference between client’s measurements and pattern measurements is enough to see that the pattern needs to be widened along all circumference lines.</p>
<p><strong>Let us think it over. </strong>By shifting the entire front side seam line by, for example, 2cm, we will arrive right at the level of our client’s under-bust line. The side seams will get shifted toward the front of the corset because the front will lack 3.5cm of width, which is a lot.</p>
<p><strong>5.5cm – 2cm = 3.5cm</strong></p>
<p>We should therefore keep close to the bust-line adjustment value when choosing a fixed value for shifting the front side seam line. Nevertheless, we cannot shift it outwards by that whole 5.5cm because the finished garment will then be too loose under the bust.</p>
<p>I mentioned it before that you may leave a little slack along the under-bust line for sizes 50+ (in this case, our client’s BC is 104cm) to make a corset with two princess seams fit a full bust well. As a rule, we don’t put bones in the cups of corsets sewn for such women with full firm breasts unless their anatomy requires it.</p>
<p><strong>After all these considerations, I suggest we shift the front side seam line outwards by 3cm. I don’t want to make it exactly the same as our client’s Under-Bust Width Front because it is rather large and, at the same time, I don’t want to walk too far from this measurement either.</strong></p>
<p><strong>I write 3cm for the full length of the side seam in column 4 and re-draw the front side seam line. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Let us look at the side back piece now.</strong></p>
<p>We need to calculate the position of the side seam line at the level of all circumference lines and choose the most suitable value for shifting the entire side seam line from top to bottom.</p>
<p><strong>It is compulsory to account for </strong>that 1.5cm by which the fold line of the centre front piece was shifted outwards and for that 3cm by which the front side seam line was shifted outwards, too.</p>
<p><strong>In other words, we have already widened the pattern by a total of: </strong></p>
<p><strong>3cm + 6cm = 9cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>Let’s start from the bust line or Bust Circumference. </strong>It is 104cm on the client and 91cm on the pattern.</p>
<p>But we have already added 9cm to the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>91cm + 9cm = 100cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>104cm – 100cm = 4cm.</strong></p>
<p><strong>This means we need to add 2cm from either side of the back at the bust line level. </strong>I write 2cm in the Side Seam Back column.</p>
<p><strong>Under-bust line and Under-Bust Circumference. </strong>It is 87cm on the client and 78cm on the pattern.</p>
<p>We have already added 9cm to the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>78cm + 9cm = 87cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>87cm – 87cm = 0cm.</strong></p>
<p><strong>As you can see, there are no changes along the under-bust line at the back. </strong>I write a zero in the Side Seam Back column.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Waistline and Waist Circumference. </strong>It is 81cm on the client and 73cm on the pattern.</p>
<p>But we have already added 9cm to the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>73cm + 9cm = 82cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>81cm – 82cm = -1cm.</strong></p>
<p><strong>As the result, we need to shift the back side seam line 0.5cm inwards at the waistline level. </strong>I write -0.5cm in the Side Seam Back column.</p>
<p><strong>Stomach line and Stomach Circumference. </strong>It is 98cm on the client and 95cm on the pattern.</p>
<p>But we have already added 9cm to the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>95cm + 9cm = 104cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>98cm – 104cm = -6cm.</strong></p>
<p><strong>We need to shift the back side seam line 3cm inwards at the stomach line level (the bottom edge of the corset). </strong>I write -3cm in the Side Seam Back column.</p>
<p><strong>Now we need to choose from these values the most suitable one for shifting the entire back side seam line inwards or outwards and then re-distribute the rest between the princess seams. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I suggest we shift the back side seam line 1cm inwards. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I write -1cm in all corresponding lines of column 5 and re-draw the back side seam line. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Let us look at the princess seam darts now. </strong></p>
<p><strong>We were supposed to add 2cm at the bust line level according to the calculations. </strong>But instead of adding 2cm, we have actually removed 1cm.</p>
<p><strong>This means a difference of 3cm. </strong>And, therefore, we must shift the princess seam 3cm inwards on either half of the back.</p>
<p>Since a princess seam is made of two edges sewn together, I shift the back princess seam line 1.5cm and not 3cm inwards.</p>
<p><strong>I write -1.5cm in the Back Princess Seam column. </strong></p>
<p><strong>There were supposed to be no changes along the under-bust line.</strong> We have removed 1cm though.</p>
<p><strong>There is a difference of 1cm. </strong>And this means the princess seam needs to be shifted 1cm inwards on either half of the back.</p>
<p>Since a princess seam is made of two edges sewn together, I shift the back princess seam line 0.5cm inwards.</p>
<p><strong>I write -0.5cm in the Back Princess Seam column. </strong></p>
<p><strong>We will have to work with the front princess seam lines too, starting from the waistline. </strong></p>
<p><strong>We were supposed to remove 0.5cm at the waistline level. </strong>But we have removed 1cm in the end.</p>
<p><strong>Therefore, there is a difference of -0.5cm. </strong></p>
<p>This value must be divided between four edges: two edges of the back princess seam and two edges of the front princess seam.</p>
<p>This means all back and front princess seam edges must be shifted inwards by about 0.1cm.</p>
<p><strong>I write -0.1cm in the Back Princess Seam and Front Princess Seam columns. </strong></p>
<p><strong>We were supposed to remove 3cm at the stomach line level. </strong>But we have removed 1cm.</p>
<p><strong>As the result, there is a difference of -2cm. </strong></p>
<p>This value must be divided between four edges: two edges of the back princess seam and two edges of the front princess seam.</p>
<p>This means all back and front princess seam edges must be shifted inwards by about 0.5cm.</p>
<p><strong>I write -0.5cm in the Back Princess Seam and Front Princess Seam columns. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I re-draw the back princess seam line and the front princess seam line. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>It is time to talk about Clip measurements and about the dart which is likely to arise. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I calculate the difference between our client’s clip measurements and pattern measurements and put the results in the table. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Clip toward Armscye. </strong>It is 14.5cm on the client and 13.2cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>14.5cm – 13.2cm = 1.3cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>Clip toward Middle of Neckline. </strong>It is 10cm on the client and 9.5cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>10cm – 9.5cm = 0.5cm</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I mark the new clips on the centre front piece and re-draw the armscye and the neckline. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I shape the neckline in accordance with the chosen style. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The lowest neckline point must not be placed higher than 1cm above bust line in large-size garments. </strong>If we had wanted a higher neckline, we would have taken a totally different pattern. Right now we are working with the style which suits this particular pattern.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I draw the princess seam line of the side front piece at a slight angle toward the centre starting from the bust line, thereby narrowing the under-bust dart.</strong> The new line parts from the old one by 2-3mm at the top. This will reduce the tension in the top part of the corset cup. <strong>I prolong the new princess seam line upwards, mark 1.3cm along it (adjustment to the Clip toward Armscye), and draw the armscye. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2044.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>This is how you manually adjust the main princess seam lines on the initial pattern.</strong> Now we only need to compare the manually calculated values with the results of automatic calculations and modify the back pieces for seamless integration of shoulder straps.</p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
</div> <!-- Scope END: Article -->
